The point is inexplicable, but we ought in fairness to remember that the chilling shadow of imperial patronage rested upon Virgil. He was not only a poet but a poet-laureate. It is the poet who pens the speeches of Dido, while the poet-laureate describes the ‘good Aeneas’ to gratify a prince who in order to found an empire —dzcm conderet urbem-would certainly not have let a woman's ruin stand in the way of state policy or his own ambition. ᾖ

Although however as an epic poem the Aeneid is wanting in vitality and human interest, the praise of eighteen centuries is sufficient evidence of its striking merits. What those merits are has been already partly indicated in referring to the Georgics. Virgil is a master of melodicus rhythm, and he is a master of literary expression.
